A few things here : 

- You need to include zeroes when calculating averages.

- Your method requires 4 numbers to be called, so you do not need to count them. It will always be 4.



Try this instead : 

    public static double average(int number1, int number2, int number3, int number4) {
        double total = sum(number1, number2, number3, number4);    
        double average = (double) total / 4;
        return average;
        }


You could also put the numbers in an array and use the array length as your count, so that you wouldn&#39;t have to edit your divider if you need to calculate the average of 6 numbers instead of 4 eventually.

You would need a loop to go through the array and add up your numbers : 


        int numbers[] = {12, 2, 8, 0};
        int total = 0;
        
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; numbers.length; i++){
        total = total + numbers[i];
        }
        double average = total / numbers.length;

There&#39;s a difference between 
- &quot;measure 3 times&quot;, i.e. &quot;there&#39;s no 4th measurement&quot; and
- &quot;measure 4 times&quot;, where one of the measurements is actually `0`

That&#39;s what you&#39;ve noticed as well, because the average of `12, 2, 8, 0` is certainly different from the average of `12, 2, 8`. The &quot;average&quot; takes *all* values into account.

I think what you&#39;re trying to achieve here is to call your average with a variable number of arguments, if I&#39;m not mistaken.

In that case you should make use of [varargs](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/arguments.html) (See the section &quot;*Arbitrary Number of Arguments*&quot;).

With varargs, you&#39;re basically passing any number of arguments to your method. Since varargs are treated as an array of values, you even have access to the *number* of arguments passed, so you can use that for calculating the average.

In the end, there&#39;s no magic involved here, just sum all values together and then divide by the number of values. No need for checking each number individually for `0` (which should not be ignored, as mentioned).

Depending on your knowledge so far, you&#39;d need to learn about [Arrays](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/arrays.html) as well, but the final code might look like this.

    public static double average(int... values) {
        double sum = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i &lt; values.length; i++) {
            sum += values[i];
        }
        return sum / values.length;
    }

And you&#39;d call the method like this:

    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        double result = average(4, 3, 6, 1);
        System.out.println(&quot;Average: &quot; + result);

        result = average(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8); // virtually any number of arguments is fine
        System.out.println(&quot;Average: &quot; + result);
    }

